SIMPLE: irony
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Irony
<hw>I"ron*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Iron</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Made or consisting of iron; partaking of iron; iron;
<as>as, <ex>irony</ex> chains; <ex>irony</ex> particles</as>; -- In this
sense <altname>iron</altname> is the more common term.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Woodward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling iron in taste, hardness, or other
physical property.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Irony</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Irony
<hw>I"ron*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ironia</ets>,
Gr. <?/ dissimulation, fr. <?/ a dissembler in speech, fr. <?/ to speak;
perh. akin to E. <ets>word</ets>: cf. F. <ets>ironie</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Dissimulation; ignorance feigned for the purpose of
confounding or provoking an antagonist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sort of humor, ridicule, or light sarcasm, which
adopts a mode of speech the meaning of which is contrary to the literal
sense of the words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iroquois</ent>⟦br⟧
